<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911125-0021</DOCNO><DOCID>911125-0021.</DOCID><HL>   Stop andamp; Shop Offering   Raises $212.5 Million   After Price Is Cut</HL><DATE>11/25/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10</SO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>FOOD RETAILERS AND WHOLESALERS, CONVENIENCE STORES (FDR)INITIAL STOCK OFFERINGS (INI)STOCK AND BOND REGISTRATIONS, PRICINGS (REG)STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)</IN><NS>INITIAL PUBLIC OFFERINGS (INI)BOND AND STOCK REGISTRATIONS AND PRICINGS (REG)STOCK andamp; OTHER MARKET NEWS (STK)</NS><RE>MASSACHUSETTS (MA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Stop andamp; Shop Cos. raised $212.5 million in an initialpublic offering after lowering the share price to completethe transaction.   The Boston-based grocery chain and operator of Bradlee'sdiscount stores originally had planned to sell 17 millionshares at $14 to $16 each. But an overall stock market slumpthe past two weeks caused Stop andamp; Shop and its underwriters,led by Merrill Lynch andamp; Co., to cut the asking price to $12.50each.</LP><TEXT>   Proceeds from the offering will be used to repay junk-bonddebt. Stop andamp; Shop was taken private by Kohlberg KravisRoberts andamp; Co. in a $1.2 billion leveraged buy-out in 1988.With the completion of the offering, public investors own 33%of Stop andamp; Shop, KKR owns 59% and current and formermanagement of the company owns the rest.   In Friday's New York Stock Exchange trading, Stop andamp; Shopwas the most active issue, on composite volume of more thanfive million shares. The stock closed unchanged at $12.50.   KKR, which controls Stop andamp; Shop through a series oflimited partnerships, didn't sell any shares of Stop andamp; Shopin the offering. Even at the reduced new-issue price of$12.50, KKR and its limited partner investors show sizablepaper profits on their 1988 investment; they paid $3.33 ashare for their stock in the company at the time of thebuy-out.</TEXT></DOC>